Key Concepts Reviewed

Business Impact Analysis (BIA)
Evaluates the potential operational and financial impact of system disruptions. BIA helps prioritize recovery efforts by identifying critical business functions and acceptable downtime.

File Integrity Monitoring (FIM)
Detects and alerts on unauthorized changes to critical files, configurations, and directories. Commonly used to protect sensitive data (e.g., PII) and ensure system integrity.

Zero Trust Security Model
Enforces strict access controls by assuming no implicit trustâ€”every request must be authenticated and authorized. Reduces attack surface and lateral movement within networks.

Memory Injection Vulnerabilities
Allow attackers to execute malicious code in memory, often bypassing traditional disk-based detection methods. Commonly associated with abnormal outbound traffic and command execution.

Vulnerability Scanning
Regular scans help identify missing patches, misconfigurations, and known vulnerabilities across endpoints and systems.

Data Ownership
The data owner is responsible for classifying data, defining access controls, and ensuring appropriate security protections are applied.

High Availability & Load Balancing
Load balancers distribute traffic across multiple servers to prevent overload and maintain service availability during failures.

Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)
Exploits authenticated user sessions by tricking browsers into executing unauthorized actions without user consent.

Wireless Channel Interference
Overlapping Wi-Fi channels degrade performance. Proper channel planning (using non-overlapping channels, especially in the 2.4 GHz band) reduces interference.

Standardizing Security Programs
Organizations can align security posture by adopting a common cybersecurity framework (CSF), enabling consistent controls, risk language, and governance across environments.

